This issue is still showing up for any `double` column type (like `real`, `double precision` etc.) with MySQL 5.7.

You can resolve it by providing the `precision` option manually to `22`

```js
@Column({ type: 'double', nullable: true, precision: 22 })
size: number;
```

This problem is hapening with Mariadb as well.  (typeorm version 0.2.31)

In my case, the generated migration for datetime says "create table ...... someColumn DATETIME NULL"
The thing is.... Mariadb, for some reason, store the column as 'DATETIME NULL DEFAULT NULL'. 

I've checked this by generating a table DDL create on dbeaver.
The typeorm migrations logic believes that the entity schema is different from database. Therefore always generating a duplicated change with no real effect.

My 'solution' was to add the default on the column definition....
@Column({
    nullable: true,
    default: () => 'NULL', // <----------- redundant
  })
  dataNas?: Date;
